    {
      "layout": "section_divider",
      "content": {
        "punchline": "Fur-released transport relief, not the respiratory arm, carries the Layer-1 fitness signal.",
        "substory_number": 1
      },
      "speaker_notes": "S1 opens the five-layer mechanism story with the question Zik 2022 raised but did not fully quantify: when *Caulobacter* loses lipid A through the \u0394lpxc deletion, does Fur derepression reshape envelope transport \u2014 and does that relief carry a measurable fitness benefit? Zik and colleagues established, in Cell Reports (PMID 35649364), that both \u0394fur and anionic sphingolipids are required for rescue, and that \"alterations in Fur-regulated processes, rather than iron status per se, underlie the ability to survive when lipid A synthesis is blocked.\" What remained unresolved is which arm of the Fur regulon is load-bearing.\n\nThe Fur regulon in *Caulobacter* controls dozens of TonB-dependent transporters and iron-uptake systems held under Fe-Fur repression in wild type, as characterized by Leaden 2018 (Front. Microbiol.) and da Silva Neto 2009 (Nucleic Acids Res.). The Zik 2022 rescue background also carries \u0394sspb, which buffers the cbb3/cyd/fix-NOPQ micro-aerobic respiratory operon at the transcript level through the SspB/ClpXP proteolytic adaptor (Bhat 2013). Two arms release when Fur is deleted in the \u0394sspb background; the question is whether fitness benefit rides on both, or just one.\n\nThis substory covers three analyses in sequence: a methods slide establishing the Spearman concordance design and the BERDL Fitness Browser calibration baseline; the NB00 orientation figure delivering a conceptual reframing before formal testing began; and a data table presenting the hypergeometric H2 verdict. The conclusion slide names the Layer-1 finding explicitly \u2014 transport arm carries the signal, respiratory arm does not. The planned negative result for the respiratory arm sharpens the story rather than weakening it: it defines precisely what Layer 1 claims, not merely what it is consistent with. This substory is the opening bracket of the throughline's five-layer architecture; the audience needs the honest Layer-1 verdict in hand before Layers 2\u20135 build on it.",
      "id": 5,
      "substory_id": "S1",
      "position": 5
    },
    {
      "layout": "methods_summary",
      "content": {
        "title": "Methods: Fur-concordance and fitness ranking to define the Layer-1 gene sets",
        "bullets": [
          "Re-analyzed Leaden 2018 \u0394fur RNA-seq (93 DEGs from supplementary Table 2) via Spearman concordance with our 4584-vs-4580 contrast (\u0394fur \u0394sspb \u0394rsab vs \u0394rsab alone)",
          "Partitioned Fur-released genes into Path A (concordant_strong, n=32 \u2014 Fur-released TBDTs and iron-uptake systems) and Path B (SspB-buffered, n=26 fitness-scored \u2014 cbb3/cyd/fix-NOPQ respiratory operon)",
          "Fitness ranking: queried BERDL kescience_fitnessbrowser (198 Caulobacter experiments; 22 envelope-stress) for phenotype-bearing rate (|t| > 4 in \u22652 envelope-stress experiments)",
          "Iron-limitation arm descoped at preflight: 0 of 198 Caulobacter FB experiments are iron-limitation; H2 reduced to envelope-axis only",
          "Computed genome background phenotype-bearing rate as calibration baseline (n=3,943 Caulobacter genes; K=1,311 phenotype-bearing = 33.25%)",
          "Applied hypergeometric enrichment test vs genome background as formal H2 verdict (pre-registered \u226510% threshold sits below background rate \u2014 recalibrated post-adversarial-review)"
        ],
        "tools_versions": [
          {
            "tool": "Fitness Browser",
            "version": "unknown"
          }
        ],
        "see_notes_footer": true
      },
      "speaker_notes": "The Layer-1 analysis runs in two conceptually distinct steps, and the speaker should arm the audience with two numbers before the results slides arrive: Spearman rho=0.315, which defines the concordance that partitions the gene sets, and 33.25%, which is the genome background rate that anchors the hypergeometric baseline.\n\nStep one is gene-set identification. We compared our 4584-vs-4580 contrast \u2014 \u0394fur \u0394sspb \u0394rsab versus \u0394rsab alone \u2014 against the 93 differentially expressed genes from Leaden 2018's published \u0394fur *Caulobacter* RNA-seq (Front. Microbiol., PMC6120978), extracted from their supplementary Table 2. Spearman concordance across those 93 DEGs yielded rho=0.315, p=2.08e-03, 71% sign concordance \u2014 confirming Fur derepression as a major driver of the 4584-vs-4580 signal. This concordance produced the partition: Path A genes are concordant_strong \u2014 up in both Leaden and our data; Path B genes are SspB-buffered \u2014 up in Leaden with logFC values from \u22125 to \u22129 but near zero in our \u0394fur \u0394sspb data, because SspB deletion prevents ClpXP-mediated degradation of the respiratory chain regulators. The partition rests on the established SspB/ClpXP adaptor mechanism confirmed in *Caulobacter* by Bhat 2013.\n\nStep two is fitness ranking. BERDL's kescience_fitnessbrowser provides 198 RB-TnSeq fitness experiments for *Caulobacter* NA1000 (Price 2018, Nature). Of these, 22 are envelope-stress conditions \u2014 vancomycin, polymyxin, SDS, bile \u2014 the relevant phenotypic axis for H2. There are zero iron-limitation experiments in the compendium: the iron-axis arm of H2 was descoped to envelope-axis-only at the plan's preflight stage, and all fitness results that follow reflect envelope stress only. Phenotype-bearing is defined as |fitness t| > 4 in at least two of the 22 envelope-stress experiments.\n\nOne calibration lesson the speaker should note briefly: the genome-wide background phenotype-bearing rate is 33.25% \u2014 K=1311 of n=3943 *Caulobacter* genes. The pre-registered \u226510% threshold sits below that background. A threshold any random gene set passes is uninformative about specific mechanistic importance. The formal H2 verdict uses hypergeometric enrichment over the 33.25% background, not threshold-passing alone \u2014 a recalibration surfaced by adversarial review and recorded in REPORT Novel Contribution \u00a77 as a methodological lesson for future fitness-browser projects. Deliver it as: \"our pre-registered bar was below the genome rate, so enrichment against background is the operative verdict.\" Then move to the orientation figure.",
      "id": 6,
      "substory_id": "S1",
      "position": 6
    },
    {
      "layout": "data_figure",
      "content": {
        "title": "NB00: sphingolipid biosynthesis is constitutive across the rescue strain series",
        "figure": "figures/00_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png",
        "caption": "Sphingolipid locus log2(CPM+1) heatmap (WT, \u0394fur \u0394sspb, intermediate, rescued); pathway is constitutive \u2014 neither induced nor suppressed \u2014 ruling out Fur-driven sphingolipid biosynthesis upregulation.",
        "data_source": "REPORT.md \u00a7Phase A; notebooks/00_orientation.ipynb cell 6"
      },
      "speaker_notes": "Before formal hypothesis testing began, the NB00 orientation notebook delivered a reframing that changed the Layer-1 question entirely. This heatmap shows the sphingolipid biosynthesis gene locus in log2(CPM+1) across the four strains in the rescue series: wild type (4580), the \u0394fur \u0394sspb background (4584), the intermediate \u0394lpxc strain (4659), and the fully rescued \u0394lpxc strain (4672). The picture is flat to slightly decreasing \u2014 not induced.\n\nThis eliminated the simplest version of the Fur story. The initial framing entering analysis was: Fur normally represses sphingolipid biosynthesis, so \u0394fur derepresses it, giving the cell extra ceramide phosphoglycerate (CPG) to substitute for lipid A. That mechanism predicts the sphingolipid locus going up in 4584 and up further in 4672. The data show the opposite: the pathway is constitutive. The CPG pool is already present in wild type; rescue is not a matter of making more sphingolipid in response to lipid A loss, but of routing an existing pool into a new function.\n\nThis observation redirected the analysis to the productive framing. The question shifted from \"why does \u0394fur induce sphingolipid biosynthesis?\" to \"given that the CPG pool is already standing, what Fur-released components enable its trafficking into the outer membrane?\" Uchendu 2026 (bioRxiv, doi:10.1101/2026.04.12.717747) provides the mechanistic hypothesis: homologs of inner-membrane Lpt transport proteins are required for sphingolipid transport in lipid-A-deficient *Caulobacter*. The Path A TBDTs and iron-uptake systems derepressed by \u0394fur are, on this model, candidate components facilitating CPG routing via the shared Lpt apparatus.\n\nOne caveat the speaker must carry: this orientation figure uses CPM normalization from NB00 and is descriptive, not formally DE-tested with FDR correction. The rigorous statistical confirmation of constitutivity \u2014 spt logFC \u22120.64 FDR 0.002, sphk \u22120.40 FDR 0.02, zero of six biosynthesis genes significantly up \u2014 belongs to NB04 in Layer 3. What this slide establishes is the conceptual reframing; the statistical support comes later. Deliver the distinction cleanly: \"NB00 showed us the CPG pool is already standing in wild type \u2014 the Layer-1 question is what Fur derepression releases to route it into the outer membrane.\" Transition: with the simplest Fur story ruled out, we turn to the fitness compendium to ask which Fur-released arm carries phenotypic weight under envelope stress.",
