      "substory_id": "S1",
      "position": 7
    },
    {
      "layout": "data_table",
      "content": {
        "title": "Path A transport genes show marginal enrichment; Path B respiratory set is background-equivalent",
        "columns": [
          "Gene set",
          "n",
          "Phenotype-bearing (%)",
          "Fold vs background",
          "p",
          "Verdict"
        ],
        "rows": [
          [
            "Path A \u2014 Fur-released TBDTs",
            "32",
            "53.1% (17/32)",
            "1.60\u00d7",
            "0.016",
            "Marginally enriched"
          ],
          [
            "Path B \u2014 SspB-buffered respiratory",
            "26",
            "34.6% (9/26)",
            "1.04\u00d7",
            "0.515",
            "Not enriched"
          ],
          [
            "Genome background (all Caulobacter)",
            "3,943",
            "33.25% (1,311/3,943)",
            "1.00\u00d7",
            "\u2014",
            "Baseline"
          ]
        ],
        "caption": "Hypergeometric enrichment of Fur-released gene sets vs genome background; Path A per-gene highlights: ChvT (CCNA_03108) |t|=43.7, TBDTs CCNA_02910/00210/02048/00028 |t| 9\u201328.",
        "footnote": "Full phenotype ranking in REPORT.md \u00a7Finding 2; notebooks/02b_h2_hypergeometric_verdict.ipynb cell 1.",
        "data_source": "REPORT.md \u00a7Finding 2 table; notebooks/02b_h2_hypergeometric_verdict.ipynb cell 1",
        "highlight_rows": [
          0
        ]
      },
      "speaker_notes": "This table delivers the formal H2 verdict: hypergeometric enrichment of the two Fur-released gene sets against the 33.25% *Caulobacter* genome background. The result is strikingly asymmetric, and the speaker's job here is to read both numbers at their actual evidence level \u2014 not to promote Path A beyond what p=0.016 warrants, and not to soften the Path B negative.\n\nPath A \u2014 the 32 concordant_strong Fur-released TBDTs and iron-uptake systems \u2014 shows 17 of 32 genes phenotype-bearing under the 22 envelope-stress experiments: 53.1%, fold enrichment 1.60\u00d7, hypergeometric p=0.016. That is marginal but real enrichment above the 33.25% genome background. The per-gene signals within Path A are what make this finding credible: ChvT (CCNA_03108) carries |t|=43.7 under envelope stress \u2014 an exceptionally large per-gene effect for a single TonB-dependent transporter. The TBDT cluster CCNA_02910, 00210, 02048, and 00028 shows |t| ranging from 9 to 28, well above background noise. Large individual signals within a marginal ensemble enrichment are consistent with a real transport-layer contribution concentrated in a subset of Path A, not a random artifact of gene-set size.\n\nPath B \u2014 the 26 SspB-buffered genes dominated by the cbb3/cyd/fix-NOPQ micro-aerobic respiratory operon \u2014 shows 9 of 26 genes phenotype-bearing: 34.6%, fold enrichment 1.04\u00d7, p=0.515. Statistically indistinguishable from the 33.25% genome background. The transcript-level buffering by \u0394sspb on the respiratory chain is real \u2014 53 of 93 Leaden \u0394fur DEGs are blunted at logFC ~0 in our \u0394fur \u0394sspb data despite \u22125 to \u22129 logFC values in Leaden \u2014 but the fitness data provide no independent evidence that these specific respiratory genes are more critical under envelope stress than any randomly chosen *Caulobacter* gene.\n\nTwo delivery caveats. First, Path A enrichment is marginal: p just below 0.05, fold 1.60\u00d7, and the pre-registration threshold was miscalibrated below background. Speaker language should be \"consistent with a fitness-bearing transport arm,\" not \"transport criticality demonstrated.\" Second, Path B failure is a clean negative at the ensemble level; individual respiratory chain genes might still matter singly, but the ensemble test cannot detect single-gene contributions within a background-equivalent set. Deliver both qualifiers directly \u2014 this precision lets the speaker defend the Layer-1 claim in Q&A rather than retreat from an overstatement.",
      "id": 8,
      "substory_id": "S1",
      "position": 8
    },
    {
      "layout": "claim_evidence",
      "content": {
        "title": "Fur-released transport relief, not the respiratory arm, carries the Layer-1 fitness signal.",
        "bullets": [
          "Fur\u2013Leaden concordance: Spearman rho=0.315, p=2.08e-03, 71% sign concordance across 93 DEGs \u2014 Fur derepression confirmed as major driver; 53 of 93 Leaden DEGs buffered at transcript level by \u0394sspb",
          "Path A (n=32 Fur-released TBDTs): fold enrichment 1.60\u00d7, p=0.016 \u2014 marginal but real enrichment above 33.25% genome background; ChvT (CCNA_03108) |t|=43.7 top per-gene signal",
          "Path B (n=26 SspB-buffered respiratory): fold 1.04\u00d7, p=0.515 \u2014 indistinguishable from background; iron axis untestable (0/198 Caulobacter FB experiments under iron limitation)"
        ],
        "citations": [
          "Leaden2018",
          "Zik2022",
          "Price2018"
        ]
      },
      "speaker_notes": "Pulling Layer 1 together: Fur derepression in the \u0394lpxc rescue background releases the 32-gene Path A transport machinery \u2014 TBDTs and iron-uptake systems \u2014 that is marginally but demonstrably enriched for envelope-stress fitness phenotypes. The 26-gene SspB-buffered respiratory arm is not enriched. The Layer-1 fitness signal is in the transport arm.\n\nThe evidence base has two direct findings and one partial finding. Direct (A1): Spearman rho=0.315, p=2.08e-03 over 93 Leaden \u0394fur DEGs with 71% sign concordance confirms Fur derepression as a major driver of the 4584-vs-4580 signal \u2014 the foundation that defines both gene sets. Direct (A5): Path B fold enrichment 1.04\u00d7, p=0.515 \u2014 the clean negative that demotes the respiratory hypothesis; direct evidence that the SspB-buffered respiratory genes are background-equivalent under envelope stress. The \"respiratory ATP required for envelope remodeling\" framing from earlier drafts of this work is hereby demoted to working hypothesis. Partial (A4): Path A fold enrichment 1.60\u00d7, p=0.016 \u2014 marginal enrichment against a 33.25% background, with the pre-registration threshold miscalibration acknowledged. Speaker language: \"consistent with a fitness-bearing transport arm,\" not \"transport criticality conclusively established.\"\n\nTwo scope qualifiers. First, the iron-limitation arm of H2 is untestable in the current compendium: zero of 198 *Caulobacter* Fitness Browser experiments are under iron limitation. Whether the same Path A transporters that score under envelope stress also score under iron limitation \u2014 their canonical Fur-regulated context \u2014 requires future RB-TnSeq experiments under bipyridyl chelation or hemin stress. Second, the mechanistic link from \"Path A genes carry envelope-stress fitness signal\" to \"specifically CPG trafficking via the shared Lpt apparatus\" is grounded in Uchendu 2026 (bioRxiv) as an inference, not a direct measurement from this project's data. The fitness result establishes which gene set carries the signal; the trafficking mechanism is the Uchendu model that makes structural sense of it and will be tested by the replication proteomics scheduled for summer 2026.\n\nTransition to S2: ChvT (CCNA_03108), the top Path A fitness hit at |t|=43.7, also appears in the late-consequence ChvI cohort identified in NB03. The ChvI envelope-stress two-component system organizes the broader transcriptional response to lipid A loss over time. S2 asks whether ChvI's engagement is real, what its temporal structure looks like, and whether it schedules the envelope rebuild beyond the transport relief Layer 1 establishes.",
      "id": 9,
      "substory_id": "S1",
      "position": 9
    },
    {
      "layout": "section_divider",
      "content": {
        "punchline": "ChvI runs a two-phase cascade: regulators first, envelope-structural genes second.",
        "substory_number": 2
      },
      "speaker_notes": "S1 established that Fur-released transport relief \u2014 specifically the Path A concordant-strong set of TonB-dependent transporters \u2014 carries the measurable fitness signal of Layer 1, while the SspB-buffered respiratory arm is statistically indistinguishable from the genome-wide background rate of 33.25%. That finding isolated what is fitness-bearing in the Fur-release arm. The hand-off to S2 is precise: if transport relief is the operative Layer-1 mechanism, then the envelope-stress two-component system ChvI is the regulator most directly wired to sense the downstream consequence \u2014 sustained outer-membrane disruption from lipid A loss.\n\nChvG-ChvI in Caulobacter is the sensor kinase\u2013response regulator pair that monitors osmotic imbalances and peptidoglycan damage to maintain envelope homeostasis, as characterized by Quintero-Yanes et al. 2022 (PLoS Genet 18:e1010465, PMID 36480504). Greenwich et al. 2023 (Annu Rev Microbiol 77:131) frames it as a conserved global regulatory circuit across alphaproteobacteria with pervasive impacts on envelope composition and host interactions. The question S2 addresses is whether ChvI mounts a single undifferentiated transcriptional wave in response to lipid A loss, or choreographs distinct early and late programs.\n\nThe answer, documented in NB03, is a two-phase cascade. Using the published ChvI regulon union from Stein 2021 and Quintero-Yanes 2022 \u2014 488 ChvI-induced genes in the tested universe \u2014 we partitioned the response into three disjoint cohorts: 20 unique-to-early, 10 both-phase, and 49 unique-to-late. All three comfortably exceed the pre-registered \u226510/cohort threshold; phase structure is real. The autoregulation signal at the center \u2014 ChvI itself (CCNA_00237) at logFC +1.45 in the early contrast belongs to the 10-gene both-phase cohort \u2014 is the most mechanistically compact datum in this section.\n\nTwo findings carry important caveats that set expectations before the evidence slides arrive. The functional theme shift from regulator-rich early cohort to envelope-structural late cohort is directionally consistent with a regulator-then-structural scheduling logic but is not statistically discriminated: Fisher exact test p=0.243 on the between-cohort functional theme comparison. The SigU hypothesis \u2014 CCNA_02977 as the sigma-factor driver of the late structural program \u2014 fails both arms of the pre-registered coherence criterion: 24.5% enrichment against a \u226550% relaxed threshold, and PaperBLAST returned zero substantive snippets for CCNA_02977 in the published Caulobacter literature. SigU is a hypothesis, not a finding. What this section does deliver cleanly \u2014 phase structure and ChvI autoregulation \u2014 will be carried verbatim into S3, which asks what the late structural program actually installs.",
      "id": 10,
      "substory_id": "S2",
      "position": 10
    },
    {
      "layout": "methods_summary",
      "content": {
        "title": "Methods: ChvI two-phase partition via dual RNA-seq contrasts against published regulon reference",
        "bullets": [
          "Reference ChvI regulon: union of Stein 2021 (\u0394chv RNA-seq) + Quintero-Yanes 2022 (ChvI-responsive RNA-seq) \u2014 488 genes in the tested universe",
          "Two contrasts capture temporal phases: early = 4584-vs-4580 (\u0394fur \u0394sspb \u0394rsaA vs \u0394rsaA); late = 4599-vs-4584 (\u0394lpxc rescued vs \u0394fur \u0394sspb)",
          "DE threshold: FDR < 0.05 (edgeR); genes classified as induced in early-only, both contrasts, or late-only",
          "Disjoint partition: unique-to-early | both-phase | unique-to-late; corrects earlier-draft 'early cohort of 30' error that conflated unique-early and both-phase",
          "Pre-registered H1 phase-structure threshold: \u226510 genes per cohort required for partition to be declared real",
          "Functional theme annotation: product descriptions categorized into regulator/TCS, envelope/OM, TBDT, lipid/membrane, PG/cell wall; Fisher exact test for between-cohort enrichment",
          "SigU driver hypothesis: PaperBLAST literature scout for CCNA_02977; coherence criterion \u226550% envelope/transport/regulator enrichment in late cohort + Fisher p<1e-3"
        ],
        "tools_versions": [
          {
            "tool": "edgeR",
            "version": "unknown"
          },
          {
            "tool": "PaperBLAST",
            "version": "unknown"
          }
        ],
        "see_notes_footer": true
      },
      "speaker_notes": "The core design decision for this section is worth naming explicitly: we used a reference-regulon cross-study approach rather than de novo ChvI regulon discovery in the \u0394lpxc strain background. We did not re-ChIP or re-sequence ChvI binding targets in our rescued strains; instead, we asked which genes from the two published ChvI-induced regulons show induced expression in our own RNA-seq contrasts. This places our \u0394lpxc-state observations in direct dialogue with established ChvI biology, allowing a clean answer to which published ChvI-responsive genes are already active at the \u0394fur/\u0394sspB stage versus which require the full lipid-A-loss signal to appear.\n\nThe union of Stein et al. 2021 (J Bacteriol 203:e00199-21, PMID 34124942) and Quintero-Yanes et al. 2022 (PLoS Genet 18:e1010465, PMID 36480504) yields 488 ChvI-induced genes in our tested genome background. We use the union rather than the intersection to capture any gene that either study identified as ChvI-responsive, giving a generous reference set that minimizes false negatives. Each gene is scored in both contrasts at FDR < 0.05 (edgeR): early = 4584-vs-4580 (\u0394fur \u0394sspb \u0394rsaA versus \u0394rsaA), the Fur/SspB release phase; late = 4599-vs-4584 (\u0394lpxc rescued versus \u0394fur \u0394sspb background), the lipid-A-loss phase. Genes induced in both contrasts are both-phase; in early only, unique-to-early; in late only, unique-to-late. Genes not significantly induced in either contrast are excluded.\n\nOne methodological correction merits explicit statement: the original report draft described an \"early cohort of 30 genes\" by combining unique-to-early and both-phase into a single bucket. The corrected disjoint partition is 20 + 10 + 49 = 79 ChvI-induced genes engaged in our data. Both-phase and unique-to-early genes answer different biological questions \u2014 both-phase genes are cooperatively sustained across phases, while unique-to-early genes are specifically active at the Fur/SspB release stage and fall out before lipid A is lost. ChvI itself (CCNA_00237) is a both-phase gene, not unique-to-early; the classification is not a labeling convention but a biological distinction that directly shapes the autoregulation interpretation.\n\nThe SigU driver hypothesis applied two pre-specified coherence criteria: a literature anchor (PaperBLAST scout on CCNA_02977, returning zero substantive snippets for any Caulobacter SigU study) and a functional coherence threshold (\u226550% of late-cohort genes in envelope/transport/regulator categories at Fisher p<1e-3). Both criteria were pre-specified in the research plan before results were examined. The result \u2014 24.5% coherence, Fisher p=0.243 \u2014 failed both arms. The methods slide makes explicit what the data can and cannot support before the audience sees the results. Transition: with the design in view, the next slide shows what the partition found.",
      "id": 11,
      "substory_id": "S2",
      "position": 11
    },
    {
      "layout": "data_table",
      "content": {
        "title": "ChvI disjoint partition: 20 unique-early + 10 both-phase + 49 late \u2014 ChvI autoregulation at the center",
        "columns": [
          "Phase",
          "n genes",
          "Key genes (logFC)",
          "Phase theme"
        ],
        "rows": [
          [
            "Unique-to-early",
            "20",
            "CCNA_02794 lasso-peptide cyclase +8.6; imuB SOS polymerase +1.5; ApbE Fe-S repair +3.8",
            "Regulatory / stress response"
          ],
          [
            "Both-phase (cooperative)",
            "10",
            "ChvI CCNA_00237 +1.45 (autoregulation); CCNA_03997 CpxP-related; CCNA_02378 SIMPL +1.9\u21923.9",
            "Cooperative continuation"
          ],
          [
            "Unique-to-late",
            "49",
            "LolA-family CCNA_03820 +2.89; Pal CCNA_00784 +2.08; TBDTs; osrP; zot-like perturber",
            "Envelope-structural / OM"
          ]
        ],
        "caption": "Disjoint partition of ChvI-induced genes engaged in the \u0394lpxc rescue (from 488-gene union regulon; Stein 2021 + Quintero-Yanes 2022); all three cohorts exceed the pre-registered \u226510/cohort threshold.",
        "footnote": "Full partition (n=79 engaged of 488 in tested universe) in REPORT.md \u00a7Finding 3; NB03 cell 4.",
        "data_source": "REPORT.md \u00a7Finding 3; NB 03_chvi_phase_partition_sigU.ipynb cells 4-5",
        "highlight_rows": [
          2
        ]
      },
      "speaker_notes": "Three features of the disjoint partition reward particular attention. First, all three cohorts clear the pre-registered \u226510/cohort threshold: 20 unique-to-early, 10 both-phase, and 49 unique-to-late. Phase structure is a direct finding (A8). An earlier version of this analysis described an \"early cohort of 30 genes\" by summing unique-to-early and both-phase; the corrected disjoint partition separates them because the two cohorts answer different biological questions \u2014 both-phase genes are cooperatively sustained through both rescue phases, while unique-to-early genes are specifically active at the \u0394fur/\u0394sspB release stage and fall out before lipid A is lost.\n\nSecond, and mechanistically the most significant single datum in this section: ChvI itself (CCNA_00237) belongs to the 10-gene both-phase cohort at logFC +1.45 in the 4584-vs-4580 contrast and continues induction through 4599-vs-4584. This is direct evidence of ChvG-ChvI autoregulation sustained across both phases. ChvI autoregulation via shared promoter elements is noted in the published alphaproteobacterial ChvG-ChvI literature (Greenwich 2023); what our data add is that the autoregulation is active and maintained through the entire temporal span of the \u0394lpxc rescue \u2014 from Fur/SspB release all the way through full lipid-A loss. Also in the both-phase cohort: the amelogenin/CpxP-related protein CCNA_03997. In Escherichia coli, CpxP is the periplasmic chaperone partner of the CpxA-CpxR envelope-stress two-component system; its Caulobacter relative appearing in the cooperatively sustained cohort is consistent with broader envelope-stress chaperone engagement alongside ChvI, though the Caulobacter CpxP-related function is not independently characterized.\n\nThird, the unique-to-late cohort carries the envelope-structural payload. LolA-family CCNA_03820 at logFC +2.89 is exactly the gene Uchendu et al. 2026 (bioRxiv 2026.04.12.717747) showed induced under \u0394spt \u2014 sphingolipid loss; its induction here under \u0394lpxc, lipid A loss, confirms it as a generic OM-stress lipoprotein-carrier response rather than a lipid-A-specific signal. Pal CCNA_00784 at logFC +2.08 transcript is a cross-notebook convergence hit: it appears in both the NB03 late ChvI cohort (this slide) and the NB05 peptidoglycan-remodeling set at logFC +2.84 protein \u2014 a convergence that will anchor the mechanistic discussion in S4.\n\nA caveat for Q&A: the 49 late-cohort genes are not all mechanistically characterized in Caulobacter. LolA, Pal, and the TBDT entries in the table are the most structurally interpretable hits; the \"Envelope-structural / OM\" theme label is a directional description, not a proof of mechanism. The full cohort includes osrP stress protein and a Zot-like membrane perturber \u2014 envelope-relevant but functionally uncharacterized. Transition: whether the early-to-late functional theme shift is statistically discriminated is the question addressed on the next slide.",
      "id": 12,
      "substory_id": "S2",
      "position": 12
    },
    {
      "layout": "claim_evidence",
      "content": {
        "title": "ChvI schedules two phases \u2014 theme shift consistent with regulator-then-structural; SigU link unresolved",
        "bullets": [
          "Phase-1 (n=20 unique-to-early): 6.7% regulator/TCS genes \u2014 regulatory and stress-response machinery deployed at the \u0394fur release stage; 0% lipid/membrane or PG/cell wall",
          "Phase-2 (n=49 unique-to-late): 10.2% envelope/OM + 12.2% TBDT genes \u2014 consistent with an envelope-structural program emerging after lipid A is lost; Fisher p=0.243 (directional but not statistically discriminated)",
          "SigU as late-phase driver: 24.5% coherence in the n=49 late cohort vs \u226550% relaxed criterion; PaperBLAST returned zero snippets for CCNA_02977 \u2014 named hypothesis only; targeted SigU-induction RNA-seq required to resolve"
        ],
        "citations": [
          "Stein2021",
          "QuinteroYanes2022",
          "Greenwich2023"
        ]
      },
      "speaker_notes": "The theme distribution quantifies the directional pattern previewed in the section divider. In the 20-gene unique-to-early cohort, 6.7% are regulator or TCS components \u2014 regulatory machinery preferentially activated at the \u0394fur/\u0394sspB release stage \u2014 and 0% are lipid/membrane or PG/cell wall genes. In the 49-gene unique-to-late cohort, 10.2% are envelope/OM genes and 12.2% are TBDTs \u2014 the late phase enriches for outer-membrane building and solute transport. This directional pattern matches what the regulator-then-structural scheduling hypothesis predicts: regulatory response installed first, structural envelope components deployed second.\n\nThe critical caveat must be delivered plainly: the Fisher exact test of this between-cohort theme shift yields p=0.243, not statistically significant even at a relaxed criterion. The \"regulator-then-structural\" scheduling narrative is directionally consistent with the data but is not statistically discriminated (A11 = partial per the plan's critical-analysis inventory). The structural analysis in this section therefore has two layers with different evidence quality. The partition structure itself \u2014 20 + 10 + 49 genes, all three cohorts above the \u226510/cohort pre-registered threshold \u2014 is a direct finding (A8). ChvI autoregulation at logFC +1.45 in the both-phase set is a direct finding (A9). The functional interpretation of what early versus late genes are doing differently is well-motivated but not yet statistically confirmed. Speaker language: \"the data are consistent with a regulator-first scheduling logic,\" not \"the regulator-then-structural theme shift is proven.\"\n\nThe SigU analysis is the section's most explicitly demoted finding. SigU (CCNA_02977) is an attractive candidate \u2014 a sigma factor that, if active in the late envelope-stress context, could explain why the late cohort turns structural \u2014 but the coherence check returned 24.5% enrichment in the 49-gene late cohort, well short of the \u226550% relaxed threshold, with Fisher p=0.243. More fundamentally, PaperBLAST returned zero substantive snippets for CCNA_02977 in any Caulobacter study \u2014 Caulobacter SigU is simply uncharacterized in the published literature, and without an independent SigU gold standard, the cohort attribution cannot be validated. The experiment that would resolve this is targeted SigU-induction RNA-seq in a vanillate-inducible overexpression strain; until that experiment is done, SigU is a named hypothesis, not a finding (A10 = \u2717 at the relaxed coherence criterion per plan inventory).\n\nTransition to S3: this section established that ChvI runs a two-phase program \u2014 regulators early, envelope-structural genes late \u2014 but it did not identify what the late structural program actually installs in the outer membrane. The answer, addressed in S3, is a constitutive anionic-sphingolipid pool already present in wild type: not an inducible emergency response synthesized when lipid A is lost, but an existing reservoir that is repurposed when the lipid A slot vacates.",
      "id": 13,
      "substory_id": "S2",
      "position": 13
    },
    {
      "layout": "section_divider",
      "content": {
        "punchline": "A constitutive sphingolipid pool, moved by repurposed Lpt machinery, substitutes for lipid A.",
        "substory_number": 3
      },
      "speaker_notes": "S2 established that ChvI runs a two-phase cascade \u2014 regulators deployed early, envelope-structural genes late \u2014 but left unanswered what the late structural program actually installs in the outer leaflet. That hand-off is precise: ChvI schedules the envelope rebuild; S3 names what fills the lipid A vacancy.\n\nThe question entering Layer 3 is grounded in Zik et al. 2022 (Cell Reports 39:110888, PMID 35649364), which showed that \u0394lpxc viability in the \u0394fur background requires anionic sphingolipid ceramide phosphoglycerate (CPG), and that \"alterations in Fur-regulated processes, rather than iron status per se, underlie the ability to survive when lipid A synthesis is blocked.\" What Zik 2022 left open was whether CPG supply is constitutive or emergency-induced \u2014 and whether the Lpt transport machinery is actively maintained to traffic CPG, or shut down once there is no LPS substrate to move.\n\nTwo competing models were testable. An emergency-induction model predicts CPG biosynthesis genes going up in the rescued strain when lipid A disappears \u2014 the cell making more substitute on demand. A constitutive-pool model predicts no biosynthesis induction: the CPG pool is already present in wild type, and when the lipid A slot vacates, existing CPG is rerouted to fill it. The Lpt repurposing model predicts the transport apparatus remains maintained or goes up at transcript, consistent with the Uchendu 2026 demonstration that Lpt paralog homologs are required for sphingolipid transport in lipid-A-deficient Caulobacter.\n\nThe honest tension entering this layer: the protein-level data for the Lpt apparatus produce a discordant picture, and the CtpA LpxF-substitute candidate from Zik 2022 was tested at a pre-registered bar and rejected. Layer 3 therefore contains one strong positive finding (constitutive CPG pool), one genuine transcript-protein tension (canonical Lpt), two directional pilot observations (lptC2, CCNA_01217), and one explicit rejection (CtpA) \u2014 a textured picture that collectively establishes what can and cannot be said about the substitute mechanism at this evidence level. The next slide establishes the measurement design before the audience sees any data.",
      "id": 14,
      "substory_id": "S3",
      "position": 14
    },
    {
      "layout": "methods_summary",
      "content": {
        "title": "Methods: H3 sub-claims tested across transcript contrast and single-replicate OM proteome",
        "bullets": [
          "Strain contrast: 4599 (delta-fur delta-sspB delta-lpxC rescued) vs 4584 (delta-fur delta-sspB intermediate) \u2014 isolates delta-lpxC-specific transcriptional response",
          "Six sphingolipid biosynthesis genes queried: spt, sphk, bcerS, cpgA/B/D head-group cluster \u2014 falsification-forward test for induction",
          "Six canonical Lpt apparatus components queried at transcript: MsbA-like, LptC-related, LptD/E families \u2014 tested for maintenance or downregulation",
          "CtpA (CCNA_03113) pre-registered BORDERLINE criterion: transcript pvalue 0.05-0.15 AND protein detected in OM proteome \u2014 both required",
          "Single-replicate OM proteome: 22 proteins from sphingolipid + Lpt + CtpA gene sets across strains 4672, 4659, 4580 \u2014 direction only, no per-protein statistics",
          "edgeR differential expression; PASS bar = FDR<0.05 transcript or |log2|>1 protein",
          "Gene sets and significance thresholds locked before differential expression analysis"
        ],
        "tools_versions": [
          {
            "tool": "edgeR",
            "version": "unknown"
          }
        ],
        "see_notes_footer": true
      },
      "speaker_notes": "The H3 evidence runs two data types in parallel: the 4599-vs-4584 edgeR transcript contrast \u2014 \u0394lpxc rescued versus \u0394fur \u0394sspb intermediate \u2014 and a single-replicate outer membrane proteome comparing strains 4672 (rescued), 4659 (intermediate), and 4580 (wild-type baseline). The transcript contrast is the primary H3 readout; the proteome is a post-hoc cross-check that became load-bearing once the Lpt protein findings emerged.\n\nFor the transcript arm, six sphingolipid biosynthesis genes were queried: serine palmitoyltransferase spt, sphingosine kinase sphk, bacterial ceramide synthase bcerS, and the cpgA/B/D head-group cluster. The test is falsification-forward \u2014 if any of the six is significantly UP in 4599-vs-4584, the constitutive-pool model is wrong. Six canonical Lpt apparatus components were queried in the same contrast, asking whether any are DOWN, since Lpt downregulation would contradict the repurposing hypothesis. Significance threshold for transcript: FDR < 0.05 via edgeR. Gene sets and thresholds were locked before differential expression analysis ran.\n\nFor CtpA specifically, the BORDERLINE criterion was pre-registered before results were examined: transcript pvalue between 0.05 and 0.15 AND protein detected in the OM proteome. Both parts were required for a BORDERLINE verdict; failing either gave REJECTED. This criterion was designed to capture a borderline transcript signal corroborated by protein detection \u2014 a deliberately conservative bar given Zik 2022's prediction of CtpA as a LpxF-substitute processing enzyme.\n\nThe OM proteome spans 22 proteins from the sphingolipid, Lpt, and CtpA gene sets across the three strains. It is single-replicate \u2014 stated upfront and carried through every protein-level claim in this layer. Only direction is interpretable; per-protein statistics are unavailable. This corresponds to REPORT.md Limitation L#2: single-replicate OM proteome findings are directional signals, not statistical conclusions. Replicated proteomics to resolve the Lpt protein ambiguity are planned for summer 2026. edgeR version was not pinned in the project notebooks and is cited as the DE framework used throughout.",
      "id": 15,
      "substory_id": "S3",
      "position": 15
    },
    {
      "id": 16,
      "position": 16,
      "substory_id": "S3",
      "layout": "data_figure",
      "content": {
        "title": "Sphingolipid biosynthesis is constitutive: 0 of 6 genes UP; spt and sphk mildly DOWN",
        "figure": "figures/NB04_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png",
        "caption": "Sphingolipid biosynthesis locus expression across strains; spt -0.64 (FDR 0.002), sphk -0.40 (FDR 0.02); 0 of 6 genes significantly upregulated.",
        "data_source": "REPORT.md \u00a7Finding 4; NB04_sphingolipid_lpt_panel.ipynb cell 3",
        "citations": [
          "Zik2022",
          "OleaOzuna2021"
        ]
      },
      "speaker_notes_seed": "When this heatmap appears, the headline result is immediate: the sphingolipid biosynthesis locus is flat to slightly declining across the rescue strain series \u2014 not induced.\n\nFrom REPORT.md \u00a7Finding 4: 0 of 6 sphingolipid biosynthesis genes is significantly upregulated in the 4599-vs-4584 contrast at FDR < 0.05. The two most sensitive readouts \u2014 serine palmitoyltransferase spt and sphingosine kinase sphk \u2014 are both significantly DOWN: spt logFC \u22120.64 FDR 0.002, sphk logFC \u22120.40 FDR 0.02. Both p-values are from the single 4599-vs-4584 contrast designed to isolate the \u0394lpxc-specific response. These are among the few genome-wide significant hits in the biosynthesis panel, and they go in the wrong direction for any emergency induction model. The REPORT scorecard records this as \"PASS strongly\" for the constitutive sub-claim.\n\nThe biology encoded here is the central mechanistic claim of Layer 3. The cell does not respond to losing lipid A by making more CPG biosynthesis transcript. The existing CPG pool \u2014 constitutive, present in wild type \u2014 is what sustains the outer-membrane substitution. This rules out the simplest emergency-response framing. Zik 2022 showed CPG is required for \u0394lpxc viability; this layer shows CPG supply is constitutive, not demand-responsive. Olea-Ozuna 2021 established the five structural genes required for ceramide synthesis in Caulobacter and for bacterial survival \u2014 those genes are in this locus, and none are induced here. Substitution is flux-driven, not transcriptionally programmed.\n\nOne critical caveat must land in delivery: we tested transcript-level regulation only. Post-transcriptional mechanisms \u2014 enzyme stabilization, allosteric flux redistribution, or substrate competition relief when LPS synthesis stops consuming shared precursors \u2014 are not excluded by these data. The constitutive-transcript finding forecloses transcriptional induction; it does not foreclose post-translational flux routing through the existing biosynthetic machinery. The audience should leave this slide knowing the CPG pool is always-on, not knowing the full flux story. The next slide turns to whether the Lpt transport apparatus is maintained to ship that standing pool across the periplasm to the outer leaflet.",
      "evidence_anchors": [
        {
          "kind": "report_section",
          "ref": "REPORT.md \u00a7Finding 4 (table row: sphingolipid biosynthesis constitutive)"
        },
        {
          "kind": "report_section",
          "ref": "REPORT.md \u00a7NB04 figure inventory (line 141): figures/NB04_sphingolipid_locus_heatmap.png"
