        "caption": "Transcript log2 from 4599-vs-4584 edgeR contrast; protein log2 from single-replicate OM proteome (4672/4659). PILOT entries require replicated proteomics (planned summer 2026).",
        "footnote": "Full H3 sub-claim scorecard in REPORT.md \u00a7Finding 4 and hypothesis scorecard; NB04_sphingolipid_lpt_panel.ipynb cells 3,5,6.",
        "data_source": "REPORT.md \u00a7Finding 4; NB04_sphingolipid_lpt_panel.ipynb cells 3,5,6",
        "highlight_rows": [
          0,
          1
        ]
      },
      "speaker_notes": "This table carries both the strongest positive result of Layer 3's second half and the layer's two genuine limits \u2014 and every row needs to be delivered at its actual evidence level.\n\nAt the transcript level, the Lpt apparatus story is clear and consistent with the Uchendu 2026 shared-component model. Zero Lpt components are significantly down in 4599-vs-4584; two are meaningfully up. MsbA-like CCNA_00307 shows logFC +0.89 FDR 0.01; LptC-related CCNA_03716 shows logFC +0.56 FDR 0.005. These are the exact Lpt paralogs that Uchendu 2026 (bioRxiv 2026.04.12.717747) demonstrated are required for inner-membrane sphingolipid transport in Caulobacter. Upregulation at transcript is direct evidence consistent with the Lpt repurposing model, and these two rows are highlighted in the table.\n\nAt the protein level, the two canonical Lpt proteins detected in the OM proteome both decline. LptD (CCNA_01760) log2(4672/4659) = \u22120.47; LptE (CCNA_03866) log2(4672/4659) = \u22120.78. This is discordant with the transcript signal and is the genuine unresolved tension in Layer 3. A parsimonious reading: canonical Lpt normally loads LPS substrate; remove the substrate and the LPS-specific machinery is less occupied or actively turned over at protein level. But single-replicate proteomics cannot discriminate substrate-limitation from active downregulation \u2014 both hypotheses remain open. The verdict is labeled DISCORDANT, not PASS, and this is REPORT.md Limitation L#2 applied directly to the most visible table row.\n\nThe lptC2 (CCNA_01226) observation: transcript logFC \u22120.60 FDR 0.034, protein log2(4672/4659) = +1.08 versus intermediate \u2014 noting that lptC2 protein was already DOWN \u22120.42 log2 in the intermediate strain, so the net change relative to WT baseline is +0.66 log2, not +1.08. CCNA_01217 (Zik 2022 sphingolipid gene required for CHIR-090 tolerance) shows protein +0.77 versus intermediate and +0.74 versus WT. Both are single-replicate pilot observations labeled PILOT; they are consistent with post-transcriptional stabilization of sphingolipid-transport machinery when LpxC competition for the shared LptB ATPase disappears, but they do not establish it statistically.\n\nCtpA: pvalue = 0.048 in 4599-vs-4584 fails the BORDERLINE lower bound (required pvalue > 0.05); CtpA protein was not detected in the OM proteome. Both parts of the pre-registered criterion failed. The notebook outputs CTPA VERDICT: REJECTED. The LpxF-substitute hypothesis from Zik 2022 remains open \u2014 this dataset did not address it at the bar we committed to.",
      "id": 17,
      "substory_id": "S3",
      "position": 17
    },
    {
      "layout": "claim_evidence",
      "content": {
        "title": "Constitutive CPG pool and maintained Lpt transcript define the substitute mechanism; CtpA rejected",
        "bullets": [
          "Sphingolipid biosynthesis constitutive: 0/6 genes UP; spt -0.64 FDR 0.002; sphk -0.40 FDR 0.02 \u2014 CPG pool is always-on, not emergency-induced",
          "Lpt apparatus maintained at transcript: MsbA-like CCNA_00307 +0.89 FDR 0.01; LptC-related CCNA_03716 +0.56 FDR 0.005 \u2014 consistent with repurposed CPG trafficking (Uchendu 2026); single-replicate protein arm discordant",
          "CtpA (CCNA_03113) REJECTED at pre-registered bar: pvalue 0.048, FDR 0.109; protein not detected \u2014 LpxF-substitute hypothesis (Zik 2022) remains untested by this work"
        ],
        "citations": [
          "Zik2022",
          "Uchendu2026"
        ]
      },
      "speaker_notes": "Layer 3 synthesizes to a two-part mechanism stated at its actual evidence level. CPG supply is constitutive \u2014 strong, direct evidence. The Lpt transport apparatus is maintained at transcript and consistent with the repurposing model \u2014 strong, direct evidence at that data type \u2014 with a genuine protein-level discordance pending replicated proteomics. CtpA was tested at a pre-registered bar and explicitly rejected.\n\nThe first finding \u2014 0 of 6 sphingolipid biosynthesis genes UP; spt logFC \u22120.64 FDR 0.002; sphk logFC \u22120.40 FDR 0.02 \u2014 carries the layer's strongest evidence. It forecloses the emergency-induction model and establishes that CPG substitution is a standing capability of wild-type Caulobacter, not a rescue-specific transcriptional response. The REPORT scorecard records this sub-claim as \"SUPPORTED strongly.\" The speaker can deliver this declaratively.\n\nThe second finding \u2014 MsbA-like CCNA_00307 logFC +0.89 FDR 0.01 and LptC-related CCNA_03716 logFC +0.56 FDR 0.005 \u2014 is also a direct transcript-level finding, consistent with the Uchendu 2026 shared-component model. The speaker must immediately follow with the protein discordance: LptD log2(4672/4659) = \u22120.47 and LptE = \u22120.78 both decline in the single-replicate proteome, which is the genuine unresolved tension. We are not claiming the canonical Lpt apparatus is definitively maintained at the protein level. The transcript evidence is consistent with repurposing; the protein story requires replicated proteomics before a stronger claim is warranted. Replicated proteomics are planned for summer 2026 (REPORT Limitation L#2).\n\nThe third element \u2014 CtpA REJECTED \u2014 is the rejection the throughline committed to surface honestly. Transcript pvalue = 0.048 fails the BORDERLINE lower bound of 0.05 in the pre-registered 4599-vs-4584 contrast; CtpA is not detected in the OM proteome. Both parts of the pre-registered criterion failed. Naming this explicitly in delivery is what makes the five-layer throughline trustworthy: the project applied a pre-registered bar, one hypothesis failed it, and we say so. Zik 2022's LpxF-substitute prediction remains an open question; this dataset did not address it at the committed threshold.\n\nWith the molecular substitute identified at its honest evidence level, S4 asks whether the peptidoglycan layer itself remodels to accommodate the rebuilt outer membrane \u2014 specifically whether synthesis shuts down broadly, and whether the Pal-Tol anchoring complex is specifically engaged to compensate for the loss of LPS-mediated membrane cohesion.",
      "id": 18,
      "substory_id": "S3",
      "position": 18
    },
    {
      "layout": "section_divider",
      "content": {
        "punchline": "Peptidoglycan synthesis downshifts with targeted Pal-Tol induction \u2014 a coordinated wall remodel.",
        "substory_number": 4
      },
      "speaker_notes": "Three adaptive layers have now been established. Fur derepression releases the transport machinery that carries Layer 1's fitness signal. ChvI runs the two-phase cascade that schedules the envelope rebuild over time. A constitutive sphingolipid pool, moved by maintained Lpt machinery, provides the outer-membrane lipid substitute. Layer 4 asks whether this adaptive program reaches the cell wall \u2014 whether the peptidoglycan layer itself reorganizes when the outer membrane's lipid chemistry changes so dramatically.\n\nThe short answer is yes, and the direction of that reorganization matters. The dominant signal is not induction but shutdown: the normal basal machinery of cell division and elongation \u2014 penicillin-binding proteins, murein biosynthesis enzymes, endopeptidases \u2014 is broadly suppressed in the \u0394lpxc rescued strain. Against that backdrop of reduced synthesis turnover, a small number of specific activities are induced, most notably SdpA, a soluble lytic murein transglycosylase, and Pal, the peptidoglycan-anchored lipoprotein of the Tol-Pal envelope-integrity complex.\n\nPal is the mechanistic centerpiece of this layer because it emerges independently from two analyses that never shared a gene set. The NB03 ChvI late-cohort partition, which asked how the envelope-stress regulator organizes its transcriptional program over time, flagged Pal as a top late-cohort hit. The NB05 PG-remodeling test, which asked prospectively whether a pre-curated set of 53 PG-enzyme loci responded to lipid A loss, flagged the same gene with concordant transcript and protein evidence. Cross-notebook convergence built on independent gene sets and independent thresholds is the strongest signal this dataset can produce.\n\nThe mechanistic interpretation of Pal induction is grounded in Tan and Chng 2025, which reframed the Tol-Pal complex's primary function as retrograde phospholipid transport for outer-membrane lipid homeostasis \u2014 precisely the relevant function when the outer leaflet's lipid composition has been fundamentally altered by \u0394lpxc. Two caveats thread through all three content slides that follow: the protein-level inductions are single-replicate, and the Pal mechanistic interpretation derives from an external E. coli study, not from direct Caulobacter measurement.",
      "id": 19,
      "substory_id": "S4",
      "position": 19
    },
    {
      "layout": "methods_summary",
      "content": {
        "title": "H4 PG-remodeling test: pre-curated gene set locked before differential expression",
        "bullets": [
          "Pre-curated gene set: 53 PG-remodeling loci (penicillin-binding proteins, murein synthases, endopeptidases, Tol-Pal factors) assembled from GO annotation BEFORE DE analysis to avoid circularity",
          "Key contrast: rescued strain 4599 (\u0394fur \u0394sspB \u0394lpxc) vs. intermediate 4584 (\u0394fur \u0394sspB, lipid A intact) \u2014 isolates the \u0394lpxc-specific wall response",
          "Transcript threshold: edgeR FDR < 0.05 in 4599-vs-4584; 25 of 53 loci pass",
          "Protein threshold: |log2(4672/4659)| > 1 in single-replicate OM proteome; 6 loci pass (no per-protein FDR available)",
          "Hits deduplicated across modalities: 28 unique loci (25 transcript + 6 protein, with overlap)",
          "H4 pre-registered pass criterion: \u22653 unique loci meeting either threshold; 28 observed \u2014 well above bar",
          "Cross-notebook check: NB03 late-ChvI cohort compared independently to identify shared hits; Pal confirmed convergent"
        ],
        "tools_versions": [
          {
            "tool": "edgeR",
            "version": "unknown"
          }
        ],
        "see_notes_footer": true
      },
      "speaker_notes": "The H4 test is non-circular by design. We assembled 53 PG-remodeling loci from GO annotation before any differential expression analysis ran \u2014 penicillin-binding proteins across class A, B, and non-classical families; murein biosynthesis enzymes including MurD and the lipid-II flippase MviN/MurJ; M23-family endopeptidases; amidases and hydrolases; transglycosylases; and anchoring factors including Tol-Pal complex members. The gene set was locked before the DE results were examined. The H4 test therefore answers the prospective question \"do these pre-specified PG genes respond to lipid A loss?\" rather than the retrospective \"did DE hits happen to include PG genes?\" That is the non-circularity the audience should register.\n\nThe key contrast is strain 4599 \u2014 \u0394fur \u0394sspb \u0394lpxc, lipid A absent \u2014 versus strain 4584 \u2014 \u0394fur \u0394sspb, lipid A intact. This pairing isolates the \u0394lpxc-specific wall response from the \u0394fur and \u0394sspb background effects already present before LpxC was removed. Two evidence modalities were used: transcript significance by edgeR FDR < 0.05 in the 4599-vs-4584 contrast, and protein change magnitude |log2| > 1 in the single-replicate OM proteome, where per-protein FDR cannot be calculated. Twenty-five loci cleared the transcript bar; six cleared the protein bar; after deduplication, 28 unique loci. The H4 pre-registered pass criterion was \u22653 unique loci meeting either threshold \u2014 a conservative bar set because PG remodeling was a post-hoc hypothesis, motivated by SdpA appearing at +4.8 log2 protein in the NB00 orientation scoping. At 28 observed loci, the bar is exceeded by nearly a factor of ten; the REPORT scorecard records this as PASS strongly.\n\nTwo procedural flags. First, the cross-notebook check: NB03's late-ChvI cohort was independently compared against the NB05 PG hits to identify convergent loci; Pal at CCNA_00784 emerged as the only gene satisfying both analyses' independent criteria simultaneously. Second, two loci in the pre-curated set are regex false-positives. CCNA_00565 is a \u03b3-glutamyltranspeptidase involved in glutathione metabolism, not PG synthesis; CCNA_01833 is a glucosylceramidase that matched the \"amidase\" search string. REPORT.md Limitation L#11 flags both explicitly; neither changes the H4 verdict and no mechanistic claim in Layer 4 rests on either gene.",
      "id": 20,
      "substory_id": "S4",
      "position": 20
    },
    {
      "layout": "data_figure",
      "content": {
        "title": "28 PG-remodeling loci meet H4 threshold: broad downshift with targeted SdpA and Pal induction",
        "figure": "figures/NB05_pg_remodeling_heatmap.png",
        "caption": "PG-remodeling enzymes meeting H4 threshold (28/53 pre-curated loci); 20 DOWN (FtsI, PbpZ/C, MurD, endopeptidases); 8 UP including SdpA +4.8 log2 protein and Pal +2.08 transcript/+2.84 protein.",
        "data_source": "REPORT.md \u00a7Finding 5; NB 05_pg_remodeling.ipynb cell 7"
      },
      "speaker_notes": "When the heatmap appears, the dominant directional signal is immediately legible: the PG-remodeling landscape of the \u0394lpxc rescue strain is driven by downregulation, with a small number of targeted inductions standing out against a suppressed background.\n\nTwenty of the 28 loci meeting the H4 threshold are DOWN. The specific identities matter for delivery. FtsI, the penicillin-binding protein responsible for cell-division-stage PG synthesis, is suppressed. PbpZ declines at \u22121.08 transcript and PbpC at \u22121.15 protein, both involved in cell elongation. The D,D-transpeptidase domain protein falls \u22121.27 log2 at protein. MurD, the murein biosynthesis ligase, and MviN/MurJ, the lipid-II flippase, are both down. The M23-family endopeptidases LdpD, LdpE, and LdpF are down, as are the amidase AmiC and the hydrolase RipA. The single largest protein decline in the set is a membrane-bound transglycosylase at \u22122.47 log2 protein. Collectively, the cell has suppressed the normal growth-phase repertoire of PG synthesis, modification, and remodeling that accompanies division and elongation.\n\nAgainst that suppressed backdrop, three specific inductions stand out. SdpA at CCNA_01252 shows the largest change: +4.8 log2 protein, a soluble lytic murein transglycosylase. PleA and PbpX also increase. Most mechanistically interesting is Pal at CCNA_00784: +2.08 transcript (FDR-significant in 4599-vs-4584) AND +2.84 protein \u2014 the only locus in the full H4 hit set showing concordant induction at both transcript and protein modalities. Pal belongs to the Tol-Pal envelope-integrity complex, not the PG synthesis machinery per se, and its dual-modality agreement combined with independent appearance in NB03 places it in a distinct evidentiary category from every other locus in this heatmap.\n\nOne framing note to carry in delivery: earlier draft language described this pattern as \"coordinated bidirectional reorganization.\" The current REPORT framing is more accurate \u2014 predominantly downshift of synthesis machinery punctuated by specific inductions. The shutdown is the dominant signal; the inductions are targeted exceptions. The mandatory caveat: protein inductions \u2014 SdpA at +4.8 and Pal at +2.84 \u2014 are from the single-replicate OM proteome. Direction is reliable; magnitudes require replicated proteomics to confirm, planned for summer 2026. The transcript-level Pal induction at +2.08 stands on independent FDR-corrected statistical ground.",
      "id": 21,
      "substory_id": "S4",
      "position": 21
    },
    {
      "layout": "claim_evidence",
      "content": {
        "title": "Pal-Tol induction is consistent with retrograde phospholipid transport for OM lipid homeostasis",
        "bullets": [
          "Pal (CCNA_00784) +2.08 transcript AND +2.84 protein \u2014 convergent across NB03 late-ChvI cohort and NB05 H4 PG set, the sole gene with both modalities induced",
          "Tan & Chng 2025 (Nat Commun 16:2293): primary Tol-Pal function is retrograde phospholipid transport for OM lipid homeostasis, not LPS-Pal structural anchoring \u2014 loss of LPS outer leaflet makes retrograde PL transport essential in \u0394lpxc",
          "Caulobacter Tol-Pal is essential for OM integrity and cell division (Yeh 2010); Pal upregulation in \u0394lpxc is consistent with maintaining this essential complex under envelope stress"
        ],
        "citations": [
          "Tan2025",
          "Yeh2010"
        ]
      },
      "speaker_notes": "Pal at CCNA_00784 is the interpretive anchor of Layer 4 because two independent analyses converge on it. In NB03, Pal appeared in the late-consequence ChvI cohort \u2014 transcript logFC +2.08 \u2014 identified by the ChvI regulon partition test, which was designed around the TCS cascade question with no reference to PG remodeling. In NB05, the same gene appeared independently in the pre-curated PG-remodeling hit set with both transcript and protein data concordant. The two analyses used different gene sets, different thresholds, and were developed at different stages of the project. Convergence on the same locus across those independent design choices is the strongest evidentiary signal in this layer.\n\nThe mechanistic interpretation rests on Tan and Chng 2025, Nature Communications 16:2293, PMID 40055349. Using engineered E. coli chimeric strains that dissociated Tol-Pal's division-plane enrichment from its OM function, that paper established that the primary role of the Tol-Pal complex is retrograde phospholipid transport for OM lipid homeostasis \u2014 not LPS-Pal structural anchoring, as our earlier draft proposed. In the \u0394lpxc state, the OM outer leaflet has lost its LPS, disrupting lipid asymmetry. Upregulating Pal is consistent with increased demand for retrograde PL transport to restore that balance. The data establish that Pal is up; the retrograde-transport reading is the Tan-Chng 2025 framing applied to our Caulobacter context.\n\nTwo qualifiers are mandatory in delivery. The protein induction \u2014 Pal at +2.84 log2 \u2014 is from the single-replicate OM proteome; direction is reliable, but magnitude and statistical weight require the replicated proteomics planned for summer 2026. The transcript induction at +2.08 (FDR-significant in 4599-vs-4584) stands on independent statistical footing. The mechanistic interpretation also depends on Tan and Chng's E. coli system, not Caulobacter-direct evidence. REPORT Limitation L#5 records this explicitly: the data show Pal up; the mechanism is from the cited paper.\n\nCaulobacter context adds a viability dimension. Yeh and colleagues 2010, Journal of Bacteriology 192:4847, PMID 20693330, established that Caulobacter Tol-Pal is essential for OM integrity and for OM constriction at cell division \u2014 unlike E. coli, where the complex is dispensable. A rescued strain completing cell division without an LPS outer leaflet, in an organism where Tol-Pal is essential for that step, faces a viability-critical reason to maintain the complex beyond adaptive advantage alone.\n\nWith all four adaptive layers characterized \u2014 Fur-released transport relief, ChvI two-phase cascade, constitutive sphingolipid substitution, and coordinated PG remodeling \u2014 S5 asks whether the sphingolipid pathway and ChvI signaling that enable this program are structurally available to the other Gram-negatives that have independently managed to lose lipid A, and whether their structural unavailability explains why only Caulobacter tolerates the \u0394lpxc deletion.",
      "id": 22,
      "substory_id": "S4",
      "position": 22
    },
    {
      "layout": "section_divider",
      "content": {
        "punchline": "Caulobacter's sphingolipid/ChvI route is taxonomically restricted \u2014 comparators lack it and use other routes.",
        "substory_number": 5
      },
      "speaker_notes": "The four preceding substories described a complete intra-Caulobacter adaptive program: Fur-released transport relief carrying the Layer 1 fitness signal; ChvI orchestrating the response over two temporal phases; a constitutive sphingolipid pool delivered by maintained Lpt machinery substituting for the absent lipid A; and a coordinated peptidoglycan downshift with targeted Pal-Tol induction. S4 closed by raising the question this substory answers \u2014 why does this four-layer program exist in Caulobacter and nowhere else? S5 answers that with a phylogenetic fact rather than a signaling result.\n\nThree other Gram-negative species \u2014 Acinetobacter baumannii, Neisseria meningitidis, and Moraxella catarrhalis \u2014 are known from published genetics to survive loss of lipid A biosynthesis. None of them encodes the Caulobacter rescue program. This is not a coincidence of organism selection or a gap in characterization: both halves of the Caulobacter route \u2014 the sphingolipid biosynthesis pathway and the ChvG-ChvI envelope-stress two-component system \u2014 are absent from all three comparator genomes. They cannot run the program because they lack the component parts.\n\nThis section rests on three analyses confirmed at two evidence levels. A21 and A22, both assessed as direct evidence in the plan inventory, use NCBI protein annotation to establish that spt (NCBI 7,0,0,0) and cerR (NCBI 6,0,0,0) are Caulobacter-unique, and that ChvG (NCBI 5,0,0,0) and ChvI (NCBI 6,0,0,0) are alphaproteobacterial-restricted. A23, assessed as partial, closes the explanatory loop by showing that each comparator is consistent with using an alternative route already available in its own genome \u2014 PBP1A and ld-transpeptidases in A. baumannii (Kang 2021), capsular polysaccharide in N. meningitidis (Steeghs 2001), and late acyltransferase truncation in M. catarrhalis (Gao 2008). A24, the method-robustness check, grounds the absence claims: PaperBLAST returns 0 hits for LpxA, LpxC, LpxD, and LpxK in Caulobacter and only 1 for LpxB, while NCBI returns 11 to 18 hits per gene \u2014 approximately an 80% false-negative rate for Caulobacter's own known lipid A biosynthesis genes. That rate establishes that PaperBLAST alone cannot anchor a biological absence claim; the comparator absences rest on NCBI-confirmed results from NB06b. One caveat stands from the outset: the route-to-mechanism link for each comparator is inferred from published genetics in separate experimental systems, not measured in this project. The first content slide explains the method.",
      "id": 23,
      "substory_id": "S5",
      "position": 23
    },
    {
      "layout": "methods_summary",
      "content": {
        "title": "NCBI re-test validates comparator absences; PaperBLAST false-negative rate ~80% in Caulobacter",
        "bullets": [
          "Four-species panel: Caulobacter crescentus (alphaproteobacterium), Acinetobacter baumannii (Gammaproteobacteria), Neisseria meningitidis (Betaproteobacteria), Moraxella catarrhalis (Gammaproteobacteria)",
          "Focal gene families: sphingolipid biosynthesis (spt, cerR, sphk); ChvG-ChvI two-component system; comparator alternative routes (PBP1A/Ldt, capsule biosynthesis locus, late-acyltransferase lpxX/lpxL)",
          "Initial screen (NB06): PaperBLAST text-mining via BERDL kescience_paperblast; hit counts reported as C/A/N/M (Caulobacter/A.b./N.m./M.c.)",
          "Post-review re-test (NB06b): NCBI protein annotation via Biopython Entrez; curated GenBank records replace description-text matching",
          "Robustness diagnostic: PaperBLAST vs NCBI for known C. crescentus lipid A genes \u2014 LpxA/C/D/B/K return 0 in PaperBLAST, 11\u201318 in NCBI (~80% false-negative rate for known genes)",
          "Biological claims rest on NCBI annotation for comparator absences; M. catarrhalis PaperBLAST results advisory only (162 total genes indexed)"
        ],
        "tools_versions": [
          {
            "tool": "PaperBLAST",
            "version": "unknown"
          },
          {
            "tool": "Biopython Entrez",
            "version": "unknown"
          }
        ],
        "see_notes_footer": true
      },
      "speaker_notes": "The method for this layer is comparative genomics applied to a four-species panel \u2014 a different approach from the transcriptomics and fitness analysis used for Layers 1 through 4. The core question is presence or absence of the gene families that define the Caulobacter rescue route across four phylogenetically diverse Gram-negatives: Caulobacter crescentus (Alphaproteobacteria), A. baumannii (Gammaproteobacteria), N. meningitidis (Betaproteobacteria), and M. catarrhalis (Gammaproteobacteria). None of the three comparators is an alphaproteobacterium \u2014 the phylogenetic class where both the sphingolipid biosynthesis pathway and ChvG-ChvI signaling are concentrated.\n\nThe initial screen (NB06) used PaperBLAST via the BERDL kescience_paperblast collection, querying by description-text matching and reporting hit counts as C/A/N/M (Caulobacter/A. baumannii/N. meningitidis/M. catarrhalis) throughout this substory. PaperBLAST is fast and literature-linked, but it retrieves hits based on published vocabulary: if a gene's literature uses non-canonical naming, the method misses it. NB06 generated the original presence/absence matrix that motivated the post-review robustness check.\n\nThe critical contribution of NB06b is the NCBI annotation re-test. The same focal gene families were queried against NCBI curated protein annotations via Biopython Entrez \u2014 GenBank records rather than text-mining. The robustness diagnostic applied this to Caulobacter's own lipid A biosynthesis genes, genes that are demonstrably present because LpxC is the gene deleted in the \u0394lpxc rescue strain. PaperBLAST returns 0 hits for LpxA in Caulobacter; NCBI returns 11. LpxC: PaperBLAST 0, NCBI 15. LpxD: PaperBLAST 0, NCBI 15. LpxB: PaperBLAST 1, NCBI 18. LpxK: PaperBLAST 0, NCBI 18. Four of the five genes are complete false negatives in PaperBLAST and the fifth is an under-count by a factor of 18, yielding the approximately 80% false-negative rate reported in REPORT.md \u00a7NB06b and NB06b cell 3.\n\nThe implication for every absence claim in this substory is direct: PaperBLAST absence alone cannot be trusted. Comparator absences in this substory rest on NCBI annotation, where the method correctly identifies the full set of known-present genes for Caulobacter. A separate concern applies specifically to M. catarrhalis: PaperBLAST indexes only 162 total genes for that organism, making its presence/absence figures advisory regardless of the general false-negative rate. NCBI annotation provides the load-bearing evidence for the comparative arm of this throughline. The next slide shows the NCBI-confirmed results for spt, cerR, ChvG, and ChvI across all four species.",
      "id": 24,
      "substory_id": "S5",
      "position": 24
    },
    {
      "layout": "data_figure",
      "content": {
        "title": "Sphingolipid pathway and ChvG-ChvI absent in all three comparators (NCBI-confirmed)",
        "figure": "figures/NB06_comparative_heatmap.png",
        "caption": "PaperBLAST screen (NB06) across the four-species panel; NCBI annotation (NB06b) confirms key absences: spt 7,0,0,0; cerR 6,0,0,0; ChvG 5,0,0,0; ChvI 6,0,0,0 (Caulobacter/A.b./N.m./M.c.).",
        "data_source": "NB06b_ncbi_annotation_presence.ipynb cell 3; Olea-Ozuna 2020/2024; Greenwich 2023"
      },
      "speaker_notes": "The comparative heatmap from NB06 visualizes the PaperBLAST presence/absence screen across the four-species panel. Hold in mind that the authoritative figures come from NB06b cell 3 \u2014 the NCBI annotation re-test \u2014 which is the source for every biological claim on this slide.\n\nFor the sphingolipid biosynthesis cluster, NCBI returns spt at 7, 0, 0, 0 and cerR at 6, 0, 0, 0 for Caulobacter, A. baumannii, N. meningitidis, and M. catarrhalis respectively \u2014 verbatim from REPORT.md \u00a7Finding 6 and the hypothesis scorecard. Note the important correction the NCBI re-test reveals: PaperBLAST reported cerR as 1, 1, 0, 0, giving A. baumannii a spurious hit that suggested partial sphingolipid pathway presence in that organism. NCBI corrects that to 0 in all three comparators, consistent with the published absence of the ceramide biosynthesis pathway outside Caulobacter and related Alphaproteobacteria. Serine palmitoyltransferase encoded by spt is the committed first step of sphingolipid biosynthesis; ceramide reductase cerR acts downstream. Both are absent across all three comparators by NCBI annotation. Independent confirmation comes from Olea-Ozuna 2021, which characterized the five-gene ceramide biosynthesis cluster required for Caulobacter survival and outer membrane integrity, and Olea-Ozuna 2024, which extended the cluster to eleven sphingolipid genes required for membrane stability and polymyxin B sensitivity. Neither paper found these genes outside the Caulobacter lineage.\n\nFor ChvG-ChvI, NCBI returns ChvG at 5, 0, 0, 0 and ChvI at 6, 0, 0, 0. A. baumannii and M. catarrhalis are Gammaproteobacteria; N. meningitidis is a Betaproteobacterium. Greenwich 2023 reviewed the ChvG-ChvI regulatory network across the Alphaproteobacteria and confirmed it as a conserved alphaproteobacterial circuit with no identified homologs in other bacterial lineages. NCBI annotation, phylogenetic class assignment, and the published circuit review all converge on the same result.\n\nA partial-evidence caveat marks the interpretive step that follows from these absence data: the A23 analysis \u2014 connecting each comparator's gene-content absence to its specific published tolerance mechanism \u2014 is assessed as partial in the plan inventory because the gene-presence-to-mechanism links come from published genetics in separate experimental systems, not from measurements in this project. The NCBI-confirmed absence data (A21 for the sphingolipid pathway, A22 for ChvG-ChvI \u2014 both direct evidence) establish the structural unavailability claim. What each comparator uses instead is addressed on the next slide.",
      "id": 25,
      "substory_id": "S5",
      "position": 25
    },
    {
      "layout": "two_column_compare",
      "content": {
        "title": "Structural unavailability explains species specificity \u2014 each comparator uses its own available route",
        "left_col_title": "Caulobacter's route (structurally unavailable to comparators)",
        "left_col_content": [
          "spt (serine palmitoyltransferase) \u2014 NCBI: 7,0,0,0 \u2014 Caulobacter-unique",
          "cerR (ceramide reductase) \u2014 NCBI: 6,0,0,0 \u2014 Caulobacter-unique",
          "ChvG-ChvI envelope-stress TCS \u2014 NCBI: 5,0,0,0 / 6,0,0,0 \u2014 alphaproteobacterial only",
          "None of the three comparators encodes either component of the Caulobacter rescue route"
        ],
        "right_col_title": "Comparator alternative routes (literature-inferred; consistent with gene content)",
        "right_col_content": [
          "A. baumannii: PBP1A loss + LdtJ/LdtK ld-transpeptidases for LOS-null viability (Kang 2021)",
          "N. meningitidis: capsular polysaccharide required for lpxA-null viability (Steeghs 2001)",
          "M. catarrhalis: late acyltransferase truncation (lpxX/lpxL) yields LOS-modified viable mutants (Gao 2008)",
          "Caveat (A23 partial): route-mechanism links inferred from published genetics; M. catarrhalis under-annotated in PaperBLAST (162 genes indexed)"
        ]
      },
      "speaker_notes": "The two-column layout maps the argument onto its two evidential layers. The left column \u2014 structural unavailability \u2014 rests on the NCBI-confirmed absences from A21 and A22: spt 7, 0, 0, 0; cerR 6, 0, 0, 0; ChvG 5, 0, 0, 0; ChvI 6, 0, 0, 0. The right column \u2014 comparator alternative routes \u2014 rests on published genetics from three separate experimental systems, which is why A23 carries partial-evidence status. The argument is not that the comparators tried and failed \u2014 it is that they physically lack the parts.\n\nFor A. baumannii, Kang 2021 showed that colistin-resistant LOS-null isolates require loss of function in PBP1A combined with ld-transpeptidase activity from LdtJ and LdtK \u2014 a peptidoglycan-remodeling route that does not involve Fur derepression or sphingolipid substitution. A. baumannii encodes PBP1A and Ldt family enzymes; it does not encode spt or ChvI. The mechanism is established by Kang 2021's direct genetic experiments in A. baumannii \u2014 not measured in this project.\n\nFor N. meningitidis, Steeghs 2001 established that viable lpxA-null mutants require capsular polysaccharide. The NB06 PaperBLAST screen found approximately 9 capsule-biosynthesis hits for N. meningitidis (versus 2-3 in the other species), consistent with a large locus that N. meningitidis encodes and Caulobacter does not. Caulobacter's surface is the crystalline RsaA S-layer protein \u2014 not a polysaccharide capsule \u2014 so capsule substitution is structurally absent from Caulobacter's own genome.\n\nFor M. catarrhalis, Gao 2008 identified the late acyltransferases lpxX and lpxL, whose deletion yields viable mutants with truncated lipid A acyl-chain content and no Fur involvement. The NB06 screen found the lpxX/lpxL family present in A. baumannii (8 hits) and N. meningitidis (3 hits) but absent in Caulobacter (0 hits). The sharpest caveat applies here: PaperBLAST indexes only 162 total genes for M. catarrhalis, making its presence/absence figures advisory; the Gao 2008 mechanism is independently established in the published experimental literature.\n\nThe A23 partial-evidence designation covers the entire right column: gene-presence-to-mechanism links come from published genetics in separate experimental systems, not from this project. The left column's NCBI-confirmed absences (A21, A22 \u2014 direct evidence) are the load-bearing foundation. Together, A21 through A24 show that structural unavailability \u2014 not chance \u2014 explains why Caulobacter alone tolerates the \u0394lpxc deletion while three other lipid-A-loss-tolerant Gram-negatives use entirely different solutions. Five adaptive layers across S1 through S5 now compose a complete mechanistic account. S6 integrates them into the throughline's unified claim.",
      "id": 26,
      "substory_id": "S5",
      "position": 26
    },
    {
      "layout": "section_divider",
      "content": {
        "punchline": "Five partially independent layers compose one *Caulobacter*-specific program for surviving lipid A loss.",
        "substory_number": 6
      },
      "speaker_notes": "We close the five-layer arc here. Across S1 through S5 the mechanism unfolded in sequence: Fur-released transport relief carries the Layer-1 fitness signal while the SspB-buffered respiratory arm does not; ChvI runs a two-phase cascade scheduling regulators before envelope-structural genes; a constitutive sphingolipid pool is delivered by maintained Lpt machinery; peptidoglycan synthesis downshifts while Pal-Tol is specifically induced; and the sphingolipid/ChvI route is structurally absent in A. baumannii, N. meningitidis, and M. catarrhalis \u2014 NCBI-confirmed at spt 7,0,0,0, cerR 6,0,0,0, ChvG 5,0,0,0, and ChvI 6,0,0,0.\n\nThe closing question this substory answers is whether those five layers, each tested independently against pre-registered thresholds, integrate into a single coherent explanation of how and why Caulobacter tolerates the \u0394lpxc deletion. The pre-registered scorecard in NB07_synthesis.ipynb is the integration artifact; it contains seven verdicts.\n\nThe phrase \"partially independent\" in the punchline is not hedging \u2014 it is the precise engineering description of the architecture. Each layer was tested in isolation. Any one could have failed without necessarily collapsing the others. What makes the integration argument credible is that the scorecard includes a REJECTED entry for CtpA and a NOT ENRICHED result for the SspB-buffered respiratory arm. Both failures are load-bearing: a scorecard with no rejections would be a scorecard with no standards. Precisely because CtpA was rejected at the pre-registered bar after adversarial review, and because the respiratory arm was demoted when it failed to clear the 33.25% genome background rate, the four-layer positive claim can be stated without overclaiming the evidence.\n\nS6 unfolds in two slides: a methods slide that orients to the five evidence arms and names the adversarial-review corrections applied before the scorecard was finalized, then the scorecard table itself. Together they land the throughline.",
      "id": 27,
      "substory_id": "S6",
      "position": 27
    },
    {
      "layout": "methods_summary",
      "content": {
        "title": "Synthesis: five evidence arms integrated against pre-registered thresholds",
        "bullets": [
          "Pre-registered hypotheses H1\u2013H4 + comparative arm; thresholds committed before any DE analysis (RESEARCH_PLAN.md \u00a7thresholds)",
          "Transcript: edgeR DE on 4599-vs-4584 contrast \u2014 isolates \u0394lpxc response against \u0394fur \u0394sspb background (FDR < 0.05)",
          "Fitness: hypergeometric enrichment vs genome background 33.25% (n=3,943 genes, 198-experiment Caulobacter RB-TnSeq compendium)",
          "OM proteome: single-replicate per strain; direction-only criterion |log2| > 1; replicated proteomics scheduled summer 2026",
          "Comparative: NCBI annotation (NB06b) re-confirmed after PaperBLAST ~80% false-negative diagnosis for Caulobacter lipid A genes",
          "Adversarial review corrections applied: CtpA verdict corrected BORDERLINE \u2192 REJECTED; Pal interpretation reframed to Tan & Chng 2025 retrograde-PL model",
          "NB07 synthesis notebook integrates all five arms into the 4-panel master figure and pre-registered scorecard"
        ],
        "tools_versions": [
          {
            "tool": "edgeR",
            "version": "unknown"
          },
          {
            "tool": "Biopython Entrez",
            "version": "unknown"
          }
        ],
        "see_notes_footer": true
      },
      "speaker_notes": "The synthesis draws on five distinct evidence platforms, and the audience needs to know what each can and cannot claim before the verdicts appear.\n\nTranscript evidence is from edgeR differential expression on the 4599-versus-4584 contrast \u2014 the \u0394lpxc rescued strain against the \u0394fur \u0394sspb intermediate \u2014 isolating the \u0394lpxc-specific transcriptional response against the combined \u0394fur \u0394sspb background. All significance thresholds were committed in RESEARCH_PLAN.md before any differential expression analysis ran: FDR less than 0.05 for transcript claims, |log2| greater than 1 for proteome calls.\n\nFitness evidence comes from the 198-experiment Caulobacter RB-TnSeq compendium accessed through BERDL's kescience_fitnessbrowser (Price 2018, Nature 557:503). The operative fitness criterion is hypergeometric enrichment against the 33.25% genome background \u2014 not the pre-registered \u226510% threshold, which sat below the background rate and was therefore uninformative as an enrichment test. That recalibration, surfaced by adversarial review, is recorded in REPORT Novel Contribution \u00a77 as a methodological lesson for future fitness-browser projects.\n\nThe OM proteome is single-replicate per strain \u2014 one of the project's eleven named limitations. Direction is interpretable at |log2| greater than 1; per-protein significance statistics cannot be computed from a single observation. Protein-level signals for lptC2, Pal, LptD, and LptE all require the replicated proteomics scheduled for summer 2026 before they can be claimed at publication rigor.\n\nTwo adversarial-review corrections are integrated into the scorecard. First, CtpA was corrected from BORDERLINE to REJECTED: the 4599-versus-4584 p-value of 0.048 fails the BORDERLINE lower bound of 0.05, and CtpA was not detected in the OM proteome. Second, the Pal-Tol interpretation was reframed from an uncited Mg2+-bridging mechanism to Tan and Chng 2025 (Nat Commun 16:2293), which established that the primary Tol-Pal function is retrograde phospholipid transport for OM lipid homeostasis. Comparator absences were confirmed by NB06b NCBI annotation after PaperBLAST was diagnosed with an approximately 80% false-negative rate for Caulobacter's own lipid A biosynthesis genes. With those corrections applied, the scorecard on the next slide is the project's final integration output.",
      "id": 28,
      "substory_id": "S6",
      "position": 28
    },
    {
      "id": 37,
      "position": 29,
      "substory_id": "S6",
      "layout": "data_figure",
      "content": {
        "title": "Four-panel master figure maps all five adaptive layers onto a single envelope cross-section",
        "figure": "figures/NB07_synthesis_master.png",
        "caption": "Layer 1 (Fur-released transport relief), Layer 2 (ChvI two-phase cascade), Layer 3 (constitutive sphingolipid substitution), Layer 4 (PG remodeling + Pal-Tol induction), and Layer 5 (comparative route unavailability) \u2014 integrated across the *Caulobacter* \u0394*lpxC* envelope. Recommended Figure 1 (REPORT.md \u00a7Key Findings; NB07_synthesis.ipynb cell 2).",
        "data_source": "REPORT.md \u00a7Key Findings line 5; notebooks/07_synthesis.ipynb cell 2"
      },
      "speaker_notes_seed": "This slide exists because the throughline promised it \u2014 and slides 27 and 28 both name it explicitly \u2014 but the deck was delivering only a scorecard table in its place. The 4-panel NB07_synthesis_master.png is the integrative payoff: the one image that places all five adaptive layers into a single spatial frame of the Caulobacter outer-membrane cross-section. Walk the audience through each panel before advancing to the scorecard. Panel A and B show the envelope cross-section with the five-layer overlay: Fur-released TBDTs repositioning outer-membrane import capacity (Layer 1); ChvI temporal scheduling with early regulators and late structural genes (Layer 2); the constitutive CPG sphingolipid pool, pre-positioned in the outer leaflet by maintained Lpt machinery, occupying the space vacated by lipid A (Layer 3); downshifted PG biosynthesis with Pal-Tol specifically upregulated for retrograde phospholipid homeostasis (Layer 4). Panels C and D overlay the fitness and transcript data to show the quantitative support under each layer. The comparative Layer 5 (spt 7,0,0,0; ChvI 6,0,0,0 by NCBI) explains why this integrated program is Caulobacter-specific. The phrase 'partially independent' is architecturally precise: each layer was tested independently and any one could have failed without collapsing the others. Four passed; CtpA was rejected; the respiratory arm was demoted. The scorecard on the next slide delivers those verdicts numerically. This figure makes the integration argument visually before the table confirms it.",
